continuous-integration.md
     1вҶ’# Running `mdbook` in continuous integration
     2вҶ’
     3вҶ’There are a variety of services such as [GitHub Actions] or [GitLab CI/CD] which can be used to test and deploy your book automatically.
     4вҶ’
     5вҶ’The following provides some general guidelines on how to configure your service to run mdBook.
     6вҶ’Specific recipes can be found at the [Automated Deployment] wiki page.
     7вҶ’
     8вҶ’[GitHub Actions]: https://docs.github.com/en/actions
     9вҶ’[GitLab CI/CD]: https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/ci/
    10вҶ’[Automated Deployment]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/wiki/Automated-Deployment
    11вҶ’
    12вҶ’## Installing mdBook
    13вҶ’
    14вҶ’There are several different strategies for installing mdBook.
    15вҶ’The particular method depends on your needs and preferences.
    16вҶ’
    17вҶ’### Pre-compiled binaries
    18вҶ’
    19вҶ’Perhaps the easiest method is to use the pre-compiled binaries found on the [GitHub Releases page][releases].
    20вҶ’A simple approach would be to use the popular `curl` CLI tool to download the executable:
    21вҶ’
    22вҶ’```sh
    23вҶ’mkdir bin
    24вҶ’curl -sSL https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/releases/download/{{ mdbook-version }}/mdbook-{{ mdbook-version }}-x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu.tar.gz | tar -xz --directory=bin
    25вҶ’bin/mdbook build
    26вҶ’```
    27вҶ’
    28вҶ’Some considerations for this approach:
    29вҶ’
    30вҶ’* This is relatively fast, and does not necessarily require dealing with caching.
    31вҶ’* This does not require installing Rust.
      вҶ’вҖҰ
    39вҶ’### Building from source
    40вҶ’
    41вҶ’Building from source will require having Rust installed.
    42вҶ’Some services have Rust pre-installed, but if your service does not, you will need to add a step to install it.
    43вҶ’
    44вҶ’After Rust is installed, `cargo install` can be used to build and install mdBook.
    45вҶ’We recommend using a SemVer version specifier so that you get the latest **non-breaking** version of mdBook.
    46вҶ’For example:
    47вҶ’
    48вҶ’```sh
    49вҶ’cargo install mdbook --no-default-features --features search --vers "^0.4" --locked
    50вҶ’```
    51вҶ’
    52вҶ’This includes several recommended options:
    53вҶ’
      вҶ’вҖҰ
    67вҶ’## Running tests
    68вҶ’
    69вҶ’You may want to run tests using [`mdbook test`] every time you push a change or create a pull request.
    70вҶ’This can be used to validate Rust code examples in the book.
    71вҶ’
    72вҶ’This will require having Rust installed.
    73вҶ’Some services have Rust pre-installed, but if your service does not, you will need to add a step to install it.
    74вҶ’
    75вҶ’Other than making sure the appropriate version of Rust is installed, there's not much more than just running `mdbook test` from the book directory.
    76вҶ’
    77вҶ’You may also want to consider running other kinds of tests, like [mdbook-linkcheck] which will check for broken links.
    78вҶ’Or if you have your own style checks, spell checker, or any other tests it might be good to run them in CI.
    79вҶ’
    80вҶ’[`mdbook test`]: cli/test.md
    81вҶ’[mdbook-linkcheck]: https://github.com/Michael-F-Bryan/mdbook-linkcheck#continuous-integration
      вҶ’вҖҰ
    83вҶ’## Deploying
    84вҶ’
    85вҶ’You may want to automatically deploy your book.
    86вҶ’Some may want to do this every time a change is pushed, and others may want to only deploy when a specific release is tagged.
    87вҶ’
    88вҶ’You'll also need to understand the specifics on how to push a change to your web service.
    89вҶ’For example, [GitHub Pages] just requires committing the output onto a specific git branch.
    90вҶ’Other services may require using something like SSH to connect to a remote server.
    91вҶ’
    92вҶ’The basic outline is that you need to run `mdbook build` to generate the output, and then transfer the files (which are in the `book` directory) to the correct location.
    93вҶ’
    94вҶ’You may then want to consider if you need to invalidate any caches on your web service.
    95вҶ’
    96вҶ’See the [Automated Deployment] wiki page for examples of various different services.
    97вҶ’
      вҶ’вҖҰ
   100вҶ’### 404 handling
   101вҶ’
   102вҶ’mdBook automatically generates a 404 page to be used for broken links.
   103вҶ’The default output is a file named `404.html` at the root of the book.
   104вҶ’Some services like [GitHub Pages] will automatically use this page for broken links.
   105вҶ’For other services, you may want to consider configuring the web server to use this page as it will provide the reader navigation to get back to the book.
   106вҶ’
   107вҶ’If your book is not deployed at the root of the domain, then you should set the [`output.html.site-url`] setting so that the 404 page works correctly.
   108вҶ’It needs to know where the book is deployed in order to load the static files (like CSS) correctly.
   109вҶ’For example, this guide is deployed at <https://rust-lang.github.io/mdBook/>, and the `site-url` setting is configured like this:
   110вҶ’
   111вҶ’```toml
   112вҶ’# book.toml
   113вҶ’[output.html]
   114вҶ’site-url = "/mdBook/"
      вҶ’вҖҰ
for_developers/README.md
     1вҶ’# For developers
     2вҶ’
     3вҶ’While `mdbook` is mainly used as a command line tool, you can also import the
     4вҶ’underlying libraries directly and use those to manage a book. It also has a fairly
     5вҶ’flexible plugin mechanism, allowing you to create your own custom tooling and
     6вҶ’consumers (often referred to as *backends*) if you need to do some analysis of
     7вҶ’the book or render it in a different format.
     8вҶ’
     9вҶ’The *For Developers* chapters are here to show you the more advanced usage of
    10вҶ’`mdbook`.
    11вҶ’
    12вҶ’The two main ways a developer can hook into the book's build process is via,
    13вҶ’
    14вҶ’- [Preprocessors](preprocessors.md)
    15вҶ’- [Alternative Backends](backends.md)
    16вҶ’
    17вҶ’## The build process
    18вҶ’
    19вҶ’The process of rendering a book project goes through several steps.
    20вҶ’
    21вҶ’1. Load the book
    22вҶ’    - Parse the `book.toml`, falling back to the default `Config` if it doesn't
    23вҶ’       exist
    24вҶ’    - Load the book chapters into memory
    25вҶ’    - Discover which preprocessors/backends should be used
    26вҶ’2. For each backend:
    27вҶ’   1. Run all the preprocessors.
    28вҶ’   2. Call the backend to render the processed result.
    29вҶ’
    30вҶ’## Using `mdbook` as a library
    31вҶ’
    32вҶ’The `mdbook` binary is just a wrapper around the underlying mdBook crates,
    33вҶ’exposing their functionality as a command-line program. If you want to
    34вҶ’programmatically drive mdBook, you can use the [`mdbook-driver`] crate.
    35вҶ’This can be used to add your own functionality or tweak the build process.
    36вҶ’
    37вҶ’The easiest way to find out how to use the `mdbook-driver` crate is by looking at the
    38вҶ’[API Docs]. The top level documentation explains how one would use the
    39вҶ’[`MDBook`] type to load and build a book, while the [config] module gives a good
    40вҶ’explanation on the configuration system.
    41вҶ’
    42вҶ’[`MDBook`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/struct.MDBook.html
    43вҶ’[API Docs]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/
    44вҶ’[config]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/config/index.html
for_developers/backends.md
     1вҶ’# Alternative backends
     2вҶ’
     3вҶ’A "backend" is simply a program which `mdbook` will invoke during the book
     4вҶ’rendering process. This program is passed a JSON representation of the book and
     5вҶ’configuration information via `stdin`. Once the backend receives this
     6вҶ’information it is free to do whatever it wants.
     7вҶ’
      вҶ’вҖҰ
