    40вҶ’fn count_words(ch: &Chapter) -> usize {
    41вҶ’    ch.content.split_whitespace().count()
    42вҶ’}
    44вҶ’#[derive(Debug, Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
    45вҶ’#[serde(default, rename_all = "kebab-case")]
    46вҶ’pub struct WordcountConfig {
    47вҶ’    pub ignores: Vec<String>,
    48вҶ’    pub deny_odds: bool,
    49вҶ’}
for_developers/preprocessors.md
     1вҶ’# Preprocessors
     2вҶ’
     3вҶ’A *preprocessor* is simply a bit of code which gets run immediately after the
     4вҶ’book is loaded and before it gets rendered, allowing you to update and mutate
     5вҶ’the book. Possible use cases are:
     6вҶ’
     7вҶ’- Creating custom helpers like `\{{#include /path/to/file.md}}`
      вҶ’вҖҰ
    13вҶ’## Hooking into MDBook
    14вҶ’
    15вҶ’MDBook uses a fairly simple mechanism for discovering third party plugins.
    16вҶ’A new table is added to `book.toml` (e.g. `[preprocessor.foo]` for the `foo`
    17вҶ’preprocessor) and then `mdbook` will try to invoke the `mdbook-foo` program as
    18вҶ’part of the build process.
    19вҶ’
      вҶ’вҖҰ
    46вҶ’## Hints for implementing a preprocessor
    47вҶ’
    48вҶ’By pulling in `mdbook-preprocessor` as a library, preprocessors can have access to the
    49вҶ’existing infrastructure for dealing with books.
    50вҶ’
    51вҶ’For example, a custom preprocessor could use the
    52вҶ’[`parse_input()`] function to deserialize the JSON written to
      вҶ’вҖҰ
    74вҶ’## Implementing a preprocessor with a different language
    75вҶ’
    76вҶ’The fact that mdBook utilizes stdin and stdout to communicate with the preprocessors makes it easy to implement them in a language other than Rust.
    77вҶ’The following code shows how to implement a simple preprocessor in Python, which will modify the content of the first chapter.
    78вҶ’The example below follows the configuration shown above with `preprocessor.foo.command` actually pointing to a Python script.
    79вҶ’
    80вҶ’```python
